We offered gift certificates as incentives, but it would have been interesting to see if more substantial prizes like bicycles, hybrid cars, or electric cars would have increased participation. The value of the prizes remained consistent throughout the project, but increasing them over time could have potentially boosted engagement. The gift cards were sufficient initially, but announcing more attractive prizes later in the project might have helped to prevent the decrease in participation seen in December and January.

An ETF, or exchange-traded fund, is a type of security that aims to mirror an index, commodity, or a collection of assets like an index fund but trades like a stock on exchanges. It offers diversification like an index fund and the advantages of owning individual stocks, such as the ability to short sell, use margin, and buy in any quantity, even as little as one share. While ETFs boast these features, they carry commission fees for each trade, similar to stock transactions. ETFs also have a wide range of options available. Despite these advantages, it's essential for investors to assess if these benefits are genuine and to what extent.

For our analysis, we'll examine the ETF IHF and compare it with its top 10 holdings, which account for 63.58% of the ETF's assets, to determine if owning a single ETF can approximate the benefits of owning a diversified portfolio of those ten stocks. We'll also evaluate if there are better configurations of the same stocks that could yield a superior risk/reward ratio or return.

To simplify our evaluation, we'll consider only the top ten holdings. We'll use the current percentage of assets, adjusted to 100%, to calculate the contributions of each stock to the portfolio's Beta and return if the portfolio consisted solely of these ten stocks in the proportions set by the ETF's holdings. The results are presented in the chart below.

The chart shows that a portfolio made up of only the top 10 holdings offers a 6.11% higher return than the ETF, representing a 16% increase. Additionally, the Beta of the top ten holdings is 0.12 lower than the ETF's overall Beta. These findings suggest that a portfolio of just the top 10 holdings could provide a higher return with a lower risk. However, it's possible that the means of these two portfolios may not be statistically different.

To determine if the portfolios are statistically different, we'll calculate and normalize the standard deviation of each of the top 10 stocks to compare their combined standard deviation to that of the ETF IHF.

Dream-land is one of Edgar Allan Poe's most highly regarded poems. In "Dream-Land," Poe employs the term "Thulé" in lines 6 and 56, which is traced back by Mabbott to Virgil. Virgil used the term to refer to an island north of Britain, which the Greeks considered the edge of the known world. While it's clear that Virgil used the term, there's a more contemporary source that should be credited. Poe had a keen interest in German authors, as evidenced by his familiarity with the works of Goethe. Karl J. Arndt, in his book "Poe's Politian and Goethe's Mignon," notes the similarity between Poe's and Goethe's poems, concluding that Poe was influenced by Goethe. The Oxford Companion to English Literature describes Goethe as a renowned writer of the poetic drama Faust, which was published in two parts: the first in 1808 and the second in the year of Goethe's death, 1832. Within Faust's second part, there is a short poem titled "The King of Thule." This poem tells the story of a king whose wife's gift of a goblet leads to her death, causing him to drink heavily and cry, ultimately leading to his decision to end his life. This character and the description in "Dream-Land" share striking similarities, possibly reflecting Poe's own struggles with loss and alcohol. Faust was also adapted into a romantic drama by H. P. Grattan in 1842, less than a year before Poe used the term Thule in "The Pit and the Pendulum." Poe references Thule twice in his collected works, once using the phrase "ultma Thule" in "The Pit and the Pendulum" and twice in "Dream-Land," serving as bookends to the poem. "The King of Thule" and "Dream-Land" can be interpreted as companion pieces. In "Dream-Land," the speaker describes the landscape of Thule as dark, lonely, and filled with the ghostly presence of dead friends, seen in a colorless, shaded world. This mirrors the state of the king in "The King of Thule" after his loss, as he too is lonely and has lost his will to rule or live, stepping into a shadowy realm. Goethe was a significant author whom Poe would have known due to his respect for Tennyson. Additionally, Poe would have been exposed to Goethe's work through the numerous reproductions following the original publication.

In accordance with California law, could a customer who was hurt after slipping and falling on an applesauce spill in a grocery store be compensated with punitive damages by demonstrating that the store manager acted with malice? The manager was informed twice about the spill and did not clean it for half an hour because he was having dinner. A judge is unlikely to dismiss Jennifer Palmer's claim for punitive damages outright. To prove that such damages are justified, she must show that the defendant acted with a willful and conscious disregard for the probable harm and that the conduct was despicable. She can argue that the manager should have been aware of the potential harm and still failed to clean the spill, despite knowing that multiple customers had previously been injured in similar incidents. While her argument that the manager's actions were despicable may be less persuasive, the facts—six slip-and-fall incidents in 2009 without proper action—support her claim. On October 13, 2009, an employee notified the manager about the spill, but he was on break and did not have time. Another employee reported the spill 15 minutes later, and he responded the same way. At 5:30 pm, Palmer slipped and fell on the spill, leading to a serious back injury. She is now suing for damages, and we are considering filing a motion to dismiss the punitive damages claim. Under California law, punitive damages can be awarded for a breach of non-contractual obligations if the defendant acted with "oppression, fraud, or malice." Malice is defined as conduct that intended to cause harm or, in the absence of intent, conduct that is "despicable" and committed with a willful and conscious disregard for others' rights. This is characterized as malicious when the defendant knows the probable dangerous consequences of their actions and deliberately fails to avoid them.

Four years ago, I enrolled in a course on Islam at CBC. One of the main points of debate was whether Islam is a hostile religion. This question seems even more pertinent now, especially when considering the shift in public perception post-9/11. Initially, the media held a hostile stance towards Islam and extremists, but this has since evolved into an extreme form of tolerance for Islam in America. For instance, in 2001, it's doubtful that a presidential candidate like Barack Obama, with known Muslim roots, would have been viable.

The Prophet Muhammad's biography intrigues me because it presents a character that contradicts historical accounts of his personality. Previously, I believed Muhammad compelled conversions and subdued tribes, forcing them to adopt Islam. However, the biography portrays him as a martyr, misunderstood and humble, with people gradually coming to see the truth in his teachings.

Moreover, there are uncanny parallels between Jesus' teachings and Muhammad's miracles. For example, Muhammad is said to have multiplied mutton and milk to feed forty men. This style of writing depicts Muhammad as a humble prophet, not requiring proof but simply living in truth and miracles. This approach, however, minimizes Jesus' life and miracles, suggesting a form of attribution by Muhammad.

Many stories in the biography aim to validate 'witnesses' and self-conversions. However, these accounts often come from third-party perspectives, which diminishes their credibility. The narrative structure, with stories told through intermediaries, reduces the impact of the tales and makes them seem less genuine.

What bothers me most is the attempt to portray Muhammad as a godly, humble, wise, and gentle man. Historical records contradict this depiction of Muhammad, and I question whether Muslims today are aware of the true history behind his rise to power.

The teachings and beliefs held by Jesus during his time were initially left behind in the evolution of Christian thought that followed. Over time, Christianity has drifted further and further from its origins. Today's world exhibits an increasing awareness and unprecedented progressive tendencies. Traditionalists, who resist any ideas beyond what they were taught, may not have enough influence to steer the whole. Christians will likely gain a deeper historical understanding in the future, leading to a desire to differentiate the doctrines added over time from Jesus' originalintentions. This reversal of Christian history, which could take decades or centuries, will involve stripping away layers of doctrine, akin to rewinding the clock, until only Jesus' original message remains. When this trend spreads through the United States and Europe, it will inspire a return to Jesus' teachings, leading to a stronger, more unified church institution. However, this reverse trend will result in reduced diversity among Christians, as different regions, denominations, and divisions become more similar. Throughout history, reversals have occurred, such as when Christians were persecuted by the Roman Empire before it became Christian. Similarly, the future's great reversal in Christianity will aim to return to the source, undoing diversity in the process. A key factor in this will be interpreting Jesus' words metaphorically, not literally. Since Jesus' lifetime, the progression of Christianity can be traced back to Judaism, with monotheism, divine revelation, and the authority of the Hebrew scriptures at its core. When the Romans took control of Jerusalem in 63 B.C.E., the Jewish population was divided into various groups, including Sadducees, Pharisees, Essenes, Zealots, and a majority of common people.

The Jungle illustrates that, at our core, humans are inherently selfish and concerned only with their own interests and comfort. People strive to improve their own lives without considering those beneath them. The factory owners and managers exemplify this, focusing solely on expanding their businesses at any cost. They disregard the environmental damage caused by their polluting factories and the suffering of their workers. According to Upton Sinclair, the "line of the buildings stood clear-cut and black against the sky; here and there out of the mass rose the great chimneys, with the river of smoke streaming away to the end of the world," highlighting the devastation their actions unleashed. Sinclair portrays the owners' indifference to the harm caused by their factories' emissions and the animal waste from the pens at Packingtown. They also exploit their employees, prioritizing profits over workers' well-being, pushing them to work long hours and potentially lay them off without compensation or job assistance. In the era depicted, there were few laws protecting workers' safety or welfare, allowing managers and owners to operate with impunity, forcing workers to endure harsh conditions. The book implies that those who died in Packingtown were expected to accept their miserable lives without aid or advocacy. Workers had no recourse, as unions often exploited them for their own gain. The workers were so mistreated and trapped in this system that they were likened to slaves, "Here is a population, low-class and mostly foreign, hanging always on the verge of starvation and dependent for its opportunities of life upon the whim of men every bit as brutal and unscrupulous as the old-time slave drivers."

Numerous writers employ various strategies to evoke specific feelings or attitudes in their readers regarding significant themes. Among these methods, F. Scott Fitzgerald employs several techniques in his novel "The Great Gatsby." He often couples unusual adjective-noun pairs to create a particular atmosphere around a subject. Additionally, he imbues symbols with meaning and subsequently uses these symbols for the same purpose. In "The Great Gatsby," Fitzgerald assigns particular meanings to colors such as gold, green, white/gray, and red/pink, which he later employs to remind readers of feelings associated with important objects.

For instance, Fitzgerald associates the colors white and gray with uniformity, where white connotes a higher class and gray signifies age and dullness. He establishes this association early in the novel through frequent references to both colors. Characters like Daisy, Jordan, and Nick are often described as wearing white, while Tom is seen in a white shirt when he meets Myrtle. Even minor details like Nick's party attire and the apartment of Catherine, which is described as a slice of a white cake, emphasize this uniformity. Unimportant subjects are also depicted with these colors: Nick's workplace is described as "white chasms," and the names on his party guest list are "gray names." Moreover, Fitzgerald uses these colors to depict everyday objects and people, further reinforcing their significance.

After building up these color associations, Fitzgerald employs them to signify indifference or uniformity. This technique first applies to Daisy. After an extended period without notable references to these colors, Fitzgerald describes Daisy as "dressed in white" in a "little white roadster," leading readers to perceive her as less of a character and more of a uniform addition that Gatsby desires. This approach is reiterated when Daisy is described as having a "gray haze of fur collar" and again in a white dress before Tom and Gatsby's encounter, further emphasizing her role as a uniform object of desire.

San Diego County is highly fertile due to its warm, sunny climate. Common crops grown here include tomatoes, citrus fruits, leafy greens, squash, broccoli, herbs, tree fruits like peaches and lemons, berries, honey, and peppers. The demand for organic, community-supported agriculture in the San Diego region is substantial, with many local groups maintaining lengthy waiting lists. Organic eggs and milk are also popular. Numerous organic farms offer tours of their operations and recreational activities such as hiking and birdwatching. This type of operation allows landowners to benefit from government programs while enhancing habitat and providing educational opportunities. While organic farming can fill a profitable niche market and increase local biodiversity, it also comes with higher costs due to the need for intensive labor and management, and lower scale efficiency compared to conventional farming. Practices beneficial to wildlife, like planting cover crops or strategic grazing rotation, may also increase labor costs. Therefore, the landowner in this scenario might seek financial assistance or expert advice to balance profits and environmental conservation. The chosen parcel is located in unincorporated San Diego County, next to the Cleveland National Forest, and is part of the East County Southern Foothills ecoregion within the San Diego Multiple Species Conservation Plan. This region is home to over a hundred plant and animal species, many of which are endangered, such as the Stephens' kangaroo rat, the mountain yellow-legged frog, several butterfly species, and the California gnatcatcher. This area has a long history of human habitation, initially by Native Americans, and later by cattle ranchers. The land was part of an original homestead patent and likely used for grazing and/or wood production. The owner of the property researched government programs to find cost mitigation options for a small farmer and used an existing organic farm in the same area as a model.

The impact of culture is substantial in any negotiation. Culture is not merely what it is, but also what it is not and what it represents. It is not monolithic or uniform, and broad generalizations like "all Russians are stubborn" or "all Japanese are accommodating" are oversimplifications. While understanding cultural norms is useful, a successful negotiator should focus on how a culture's values and attitudes influence negotiations. When dealing with a foreign culture, one tends to relate it to their own, leading to inevitable comparisons. To comprehend a foreign culture or mindset, one might study its history and recognize its biases. Instead of criticizing or attempting to alter a culture, it's essential to accept it as it is and operate within its parameters, especially when in a weaker negotiating position or in a foreign setting. Culture extends beyond national boundaries, as companies within a nation often develop their own distinct cultures. Corporate cultures can manifest in dress codes, communication styles, hiring practices, and employee philanthropy policies. Even within the same society, there can be significant diversity in corporate culture, as seen in the variations between American companies. Some cultures present as less stratified but may still harbor deep differences. Values are crucial as they explain the "why" behind a culture's behavior. If saving face or harmony is valued, a negotiator will avoid public embarrassment to secure a deal. A negotiator should also learn about their opponent's personal background to enhance the negotiation's effectiveness.

"The fool has said in his heart, 'There is no God.'" This phrase is first found in Psalm 14 of the Christian Bible, and it serves as the starting point for St. Anselm's argument for God's existence. Notably, it also reflects the stance of the other thinker we'll discuss, Thomas Aquinas. Both authors argue for the same God, so to compare their arguments, we'll assume they both believe in the God of the Bible. This assumption allows us to focus on their arguments specifically for this God, as any other concept of God wouldn't be relevant to their respective arguments. While both present valid points, neither truly offers a comprehensive basis for belief in God.

To begin our analysis, let's examine St. Anselm's main argument. Anselm posits that understanding God comes through faith, with the proof of God's existence residing within our own minds. He argues that since God is present in our understanding, we can't imagine God's nonexistence. Although his phrasing can be dense, the core idea is that God's existence is evident in our inherent knowledge. This concept aligns with Christian faith's acceptance of truths that lack empirical evidence.

This differs from St. Thomas Aquinas' approach. Aquinas asserts that God's existence can be proven through reason and empirical evidence, without relying on faith. This perspective would be advantageous for evangelism, as it would enable converting people through logic alone. Aquinas presents five logical arguments for God's existence: change, causation, contingency, degrees of excellence, and harmony. In each, he demonstrates that God's existence is logically necessary, akin to knowing the features of a missing puzzle piece without seeing it.

Around 2500 years ago, a future figure, eventually known as the Buddha, was born. Throughout his life, he abandoned worldly life and became enlightened, founding Buddhism. The most traditional form of this religion is called Theravada Buddhism. Over its 2500-year history, it has evolved significantly, as seen in the annual water-cutting ceremony observed in Sri Lanka, though Buddha himself did not teach such rituals. These changes span from cultural traditions to core beliefs. Theravada Buddhism, from both monastic and lay perspectives, has adapted its teachings due to various internal and external influences, some hostile and others benign.

First, it's crucial to understand the fundamental tenets of Theravada Buddhism. Buddhists take refuge in the Three Jewels—the Buddha, the Dhamma (Buddhist teachings), and the Sangha (community of monks). The Dhamma includes the Tripitaka, comprising the Sutta Pitaka (scriptures), Vinaya Pitaka (rules of conduct), and Abhidhamma Pitaka (metaphysical concepts). Key concepts include Anatta (no-self), Dukkha (suffering), and Anicca (impermanence). Recognizing these ideas is essential for escaping Sansara (the cycle of death and rebirth) and overcoming craving, hatred, and delusion. The Vinaya Pitaka outlines rules for laypeople (five precepts: non-killing, honesty, non-stealing, chastity, and abstinence from intoxicants) and monks, with the most fundamental doctrine being the Four Noble Truths: life is suffering, attachment causes suffering, suffering can be overcome, and the path to overcoming suffering involves the Eightfold Path.

The United States and Mexico once had a long-standing rivalry that lasted from 1836 to 1893, a rivalry marked by the Mexican-American War (1846-1848), where the U.S. defeated Mexico and gained Texas and the American Southwest. This conflict was one of many clashes between the two nations that subsided before World War I. The rivalry stemmed from disagreements over religion, culture, and material interests, much like other nations that share a border. David M. Pletcher (1977) noted that only Mexico and Cuba have had enduring issues with the U.S., due to their geographical proximity. The religious differences between the nations, rooted in the historical tension between the English and Spanish, contributed to this rivalry. According to Diehl and Goerts (2000), 17 disputes occurred during this period, primarily territorial in nature, such as Mexican raids into U.S. territory and border issues. Schmitt (1974) explains that the rivalry began to ease as Mexico became increasingly dependent on the U.S. and ended with a shift in U.S. ambitions from territorial expansion to economic intervention in Mexico during the late 19th century.

Fifteen years ago, I became unexpectedly disabled by a previously unknown illness. At the time, I was a nurse, having chosen this profession to ensure my own safety and security, as I hadn't experienced them in my childhood. The phrase, "You'll always have a job; people always get sick," constantly reinforced this decision, even though my dream was initially to be a scientist or journalist. Despite being 46, single, and with no significant savings or work capacity due to my disability, I have relied on Social Security Disability for the past 15 years. My life now is a constant struggle, and nothing feels secure. However, without the support of my family and a few friends, I wouldn't have made it this far. When facing real crises, it becomes clear that relying solely on oneself is not enough.

Life always presents emergencies, big and small, and no amount of preparation can guarantee overcoming them alone. I strongly believe that we should reduce our reliance on large government systems and encourage Americans to regain trust in each other, helping one another and seeking assistance. The resilience of our forefathers was not built on rugged individualism but on compassion, mutual respect, and the sharing of resources. Pioneers didn't cross the Rockies alone; they traveled in wagon trains.

While I advocate being prepared for emergencies with supplies like a disaster kit, first aid, and food storage, I also stress the importance of getting to know and supporting your neighbors.

Why do organisms evolve in the way they do? Are there limitations that influence the path of evolutionary change? Although D’Arcy Thompson noted in 1917 that "Even now the zoologist has scarcely begun to dream of defining in mathematical language even the simplest organic forms," this sentiment remains true today. Recent advancements have applied mathematical modeling to various aspects of mollusk skeletogenesis through both ontogeny and phylogeny (e.g., Raup and Stanley, 1981). Our research investigates how mathematical modeling of ontogenetic and phylogenetic changes in Prunum, combined with experimental studies, can uncover the mechanisms driving the direction and extent of evolutionary-developmental changes. By analyzing X-radiographic images of Prunum species, we identified quantitative parameters for modeling hypothetical and actual skeletal morphologies using the CerioShell software (Stone, 1995). We generated models of hypothetical shell morphologies to understand the boundaries of possible morphological changes in Prunum, integrating these with experimental and descriptive studies to better comprehend macroevolutionary events in this clade.

A shell can be visualized as a tube that evolves over time through 360 degrees of space. These revolutions or turns of a coiled shell are called whorls, which spiral around an imaginary central axis known as the columella. The pace at which whorls enlarge varies, and a continuous line separates each whorl, referred to as a suture. Typically, the largest whorl is the last one, called the body whorl. The spire consists of all whorls except the last. The top of the spire is called the apex, and the bottom is the base. The animal emerges through an opening called the aperture.

Shells can be examined in apical, basal, apertural, and abapertural views. The "usual" orientation of a shell is an apertural view, with the aperture facing the viewer and the apex pointing up.

A method for counting whorls involves first viewing the shell from the apical perspective and then locating the first suture. A line is drawn to divide the shell into two parts, and whorls are counted from this line, estimated to a quarter of a whorl.

A shell can be seen as a series of apertures that move through time and space as the animal grows its shell. The path of the aperture can be traced using the coordinates of the center of each whorl's aperture, along with the horizontal and vertical radii. This trajectory can be both graphically and mathematically represented. Once a mathematical formulation is established, parameters can be adjusted to modify the mollusk's skeletogenesis.

The rate of neonatal and infant mortality in Indonesia has remained relatively unchanged over the past decade. Despite the nation's progress towards many Millennium Development Goals, such as those related to water and sanitation, improvements in child and maternal health are far from what's needed to meet the 2015 targets. The underlying causes of these shortfalls point to the need to bolster Indonesia's healthcare system rather than solely focusing on specific interventions.

In terms of healthcare delivery, Indonesia has seen an increase in births attended by skilled healthcare workers, with 72% now meeting this target. However, this figure includes traditional workers like midwives who cannot provide medical interventions during complications, leading to a high number of maternal deaths from hemorrhage. Moreover, there has been a decrease in the proportion of diarrhea cases in children under five treated by a healthcare professional. Postnatal care data is incomplete, but it's evident that this is also an area of concern with low rates nationwide.

Cesarean-section rates remain low at about 4%, and there's a notable disparity between urban (7%) and rural (2%) rates, indicating inequitable healthcare access across the country, with most services concentrated in urban areas. Additionally, there's a 27% gap in healthcare service utilization between the poorest and richest quintiles, suggesting that the poor struggle more to access services due to out-of-pocket costs.

In considering how to improve neonatal and maternal care indicators, the primary question is how to most effectively address the lack of healthcare services. Should Indonesia develop targeted programs or strengthen the overall healthcare system, including pre- and post-pregnancy care for mothers and children? While targeted programmatic approaches have clear, manageable objectives and can generate faster results, there are drawbacks to consider. Heavy investment in one area can divert funding and human resources from others, leading to duplication of services and uncoordinated efforts.

Victorian literature is renowned for its meticulous attention to detail and focus on aristocratic themes. Two notable exceptions are Oliver Twist and Wuthering Heights, which stand out due to their use of mystery and the unusual, qualities uncommon in the era's literature. These elements enrich the characters' development by revealing their motivations and feelings. For instance, in Dickens' Oliver Twist, dream sequences are employed to delve into Oliver's psyche, providing insights into his inner turmoil and experiences. The scene where Oliver relives the shooting in Chapter 28 is a prime example, illustrating his lack of control over the situation and the enduring trauma it causes. Oliver's hallucinations of Sikes and Crackit underscore his powerlessness, and the shooting serves as a catalyst for his sense of defeat, suggesting that external forces, perhaps the influence of characters like Fagin, are shaping his despair and limiting his ability to react.

“The day passed off – day! There was no day; it was gone as soon as come – and night came on again; night so long, and yet so short; long in it’s dreadful silence and short in it’s fleeting ours.”

A few years back, I was a tutor in an after-school program for elementary-aged students. I made efforts to assist them in subjects they were struggling with, particularly in English and reading. I was asked by one instructor to help a boy named Adrian, who was having difficulty reading. I noticed something unusual about Adrian's case; he could pronounce some letters correctly, while others were a mystery. Adrian was of Latino descent, and though he spoke English perfectly, his reading comprehension was problematic. One day, when his mother visited, she couldn't speak English, only Spanish. With my limited Spanish skills, we managed to communicate, and it became clear that Adrian's issue was not with reading itself, but with the English alphabet and its pronunciations. While I'm unsure if this realization helped Adrian, I hope he's doing better now. I share this story to highlight language barriers in schools, especially in California, and to illustrate that even apparent English proficiency doesn't guarantee reading comprehension. This problem is evident to all, and solutions can be complex. Adrian's case showed that targeted tutoring in English reading helped, but for children with minimal English proficiency, a combination of various approaches is essential. The dual language system is beneficial for all children, not just those whose first language is Spanish. It has been found to improve academic performance, but the idea often faces resistance due to fears of resource waste. Implementing such programs on a larger scale could benefit all students. To achieve this, bilingual aids or tutors could be employed without requiring all teachers to be bilingual.

Throughout our lives, many of us are taught that there is something greater than ourselves, something we can't fully understand. Some of us learn about it in religious settings, others seek it within themselves, while some of us wholeheartedly embrace the beliefs passed down to us by our parents. Conversely, there are those who reject these ideas, believing that there is nothing beyond our personal experiences. We may adopt one belief system only to later change our minds and embrace another. Regardless of the path we choose, we define a part of our identity through our unique spiritual views. We search for a beacon of light to guide us out of the shadows and into the sun.

My father's favorite bird, he said, was the cardinal. We sat on the front porch, listening to the rain batter the tin roof as we smoked. The gutters channeled the rain, drenching the plants around the porch. He stared into the rain, his gaze split between searching and reminiscing. He had lost weight, and his clothes hung loosely on him. His hair was thinner, and he avoided eye contact. I felt alone, afraid, and unable to discuss how much I would miss him with him. I hugged him, pulled my chair closer, and joined him in watching the rain fall in the June twilight.

My father passed away in December that same year, five days after my twenty-second birthday. The chemotherapy and radiation prolonged his suffering rather than easing it, but kept him alive a few extra months beyond the doctors' projections. I couldn't comprehend the value in prolonging his suffering. If God existed, I thought, he must have stopped listening to me long ago.

I hadn't wanted to witness my father's passing. So, I chose not to. I didn't want to see the creator of my life end. I preferred to remember him by how he lived, not how he died. Besides, I knew my father better than anyone else did, and I knew he wouldn't want me to watch him die. I curled up in my bed for three days, waiting for the news, but no one even called me.

The classic "Gothic Novel," a term coined by Ian Watt, is essentially an oxymoron, combining "old" and "new" elements. It has been both criticized and celebrated, praised for its 'terrible sublime' effect (Burke). Walpole's The Castle of Otranto, the first Gothic novel, blended medieval and modern romantic ideas to establish the Gothic genre. Walpole used old theatrical elements and new mimicry of nature in modern novels to create his "Gothic Story" (Walpole 4). The Gothic genre frequently references medieval gothic theatre, architecture, and traditions. When Walpole published The Castle of Otranto, the term "gothic" was used to describe various peoples, styles, and periods, often viewed as archaic or unsophisticated compared to modern advancements. The fusion of the theatrical Gothic elements with the novel's new format, which offered readers an intimate view of characters' psychologies, ensured the genre's longevity and timeless appeal. Even when removed from its original context, a reader can still find it both outdated and fresh.

One prominent theme in Gothic novels is the concept of chivalry. The Castle of Otranto retains and transforms the medieval idea of chivalry, the training of a proper knight. Chivalry is significant to Gothic writers because it represents the ideal of a brave, honorable, and competent knight, and the perceived absence of those qualities in contemporary society. By incorporating chivalric ideas and practices, Gothic novels idealize and romanticize the past, hinting at the evolution towards Romanticism, and strive to improve the present. Walpole, writing during a politically tumultuous time, may have felt that the moral integrity and inherent goodness of the Gothic era had been lost in modern society. This is evident in characters like Frederic, who embodies chivalric traits. Before meeting Frederic, he is described as a prince, having suffered tragedy and being presumed killed by infidels. His character, with its exaggerated chivalric imagery, exemplifies the Gothic trope of excess (66).

Supply chain management encompasses the flow of activities that move goods from the point of customer order through to raw materials sourcing, production, and distribution to the customer. The term was coined in 1982 by consultant Keith Oliver, who described it as the process of planning, implementing, and overseeing the supply chain to meet customer needs swiftly and efficiently. Key components of supply chain management include production, supply, inventory, location, transportation, and information. Business managers utilize these elements to deliver optimal customer service.

The first step in the supply chain process is production. This is the cornerstone of the entire supply chain. Production planning involves determining when, where, how, and why goods will be produced. To make informed decisions, managers must understand customer demands. Market analysis is crucial for determining customer needs. Once market demands are understood, managers can decide which products to produce and in what quantities. The next step is choosing the most optimal location for production based on volume, quality, and customer satisfaction. After selecting a location, managers focus on scheduling workloads and equipment maintenance. Production is a critical stage in the supply chain, and meticulous planning is essential to avoid costly delays and inefficiencies.

The second key element in supply chain management is supply. Supply involves strategic decisions to determine the core capabilities of a facility and to establish partnerships for outsourcing. A company may have multiple production divisions for a single product, each with its own set of equipment, workers, and specialties. The manager must choose the division best suited for each product process. Outsourcing work to other companies can enhance flexibility and reduce costs while maintaining quality. The primary goal of outsourcing is to achieve velocity, which refers to the ability to provide quality and flexibility while controlling or maintaining low costs.

Hitler is alive in Myanmar, the sign reads.

Ellen Page, the star of Juno, stands alone at a street corner, holding a piece of cardboard with a disturbing message written on it in Sharpie. Myanmar, a Southeast Asian nation, is governed by a dictatorial military junta that seized power in 1962 through a coup d'état. In 2007, public protests led by monks began, marking the first such unrest in a decade. Known as the Saffron Revolution, these protests initially saw monks gathering peacefully, but later escalated into violence between the monks and the military, with the military invading monasteries and foreign journalists being arrested and killed. While the official death count is 13, a defector from the army claimed many more people were killed. This is not an isolated incident; governments' suppression of dissent is as old as civilization itself. Examples include Roman emperors claiming divine right to rule, Japanese emperors being considered divine, and the current U.S. President having weekly calls with Ted Haggard, leader of Stupid People Worldwide.

Famous instances include the Tiananmen Square protests of 1989, where students, intellectuals, and labor activists gathered to protest the government's authoritarian rule, with death tolls ranging from hundreds to thousands. The Rwandan genocide of the 1990s, involving Hutu militia groups and the Rwandan government systematically killing Tutsis and political moderates, is another tragic example. Hitler's 'Third Reich' saw the systematic murder of Jewish people in multiple countries.

Duke Ellington's enduring influence in jazz is largely owed to his long-lasting career and his innovative abilities to lead his orchestra. Although Ellington's piano presence is often subtle in many of his compositions, he excelled as a composer in creating intricate and detailed pieces that highlighted the individual talents of his band members. Ellington established a framework that allowed soloists to improvise freely, while also crafting tightly arranged pieces that showcased each musician's unique style. This approach not only emphasized the overall tone of the orchestra but also enabled him to produce some of the most groundbreaking and brilliant works in jazz history.

The Grove Music dictionary highlights Ellington's sound and innovation, particularly in "Creole Love Call," where he pioneered the use of the voice as a jazz instrument. This early piece demonstrates Ellington's ability to add texture and color without lyrics and his skill in complementing his soloists' styles. "Creole Love Call" consists of six choruses, each showcasing different musical elements and textures:

- Chorus 1: A call and response between voice and reeds, starting with a smooth, melodic voice that transitions to a rougher sound.
- Chorus 2: A muted trumpet solo that builds upon the basic melody, focusing on extended blue notes.
- Chorus 3: A high-register clarinet solo backed by a subtle syncopated piano phrase.
- Chorus 4: The full band mimics the first chorus with a call and response by brass and reed sections.
- Chorus 5: The climactic chorus, with reeds initiating the call and response in a high register, backed by syncopated stop time from brass and rhythm sections.
- Chorus 6: A return to the initial structure, with call and response between voice and reeds, this time featuring the "growl" technique in the vocal solo.
- Tag: A vocal run and a dissonant trombone solo end the piece.

Ellington's use of the voice to add tonal depth in "Creole Love Call" exemplifies a recurring stylistic trait in his work. In "Hot and Bothered," recorded a year later, Ellington combines his orchestration skills with his ear for tone color. Here, a call and response between "Bubber" Miley on muted trumpet and Baby Cox's scat singing marries the vocal elements of Miley's playing with the instrumental qualities of Cox's voice to produce a rich and complementary sound. "It Don't Mean a Thing (If It Ain't Got That Swing)" further extends these concepts, with Ellington utilizing Joe "Tricky Sam" Nanton on muted trombone to great effect in introducing the melody.

From a young age, she felt a persistent craving that remained unfulfilled. This longing began when she was 14, during the earliest stages of her teenage years, and continued into her 17th year. Initially, she thought she wanted something tangible, but over time, her interest shifted to a desire for a romantic connection. Despite many boys being drawn to her and attempting to court her, she felt no genuine attraction. This conundrum puzzled her greatly, but she continued to question it, although she hadn't yet found a satisfactory explanation. She led a peaceful life with her parents, who were calm and understanding, apart from occasional disagreements about her independent nature. Her vibrant and fun personality complemented her kindness, making her well-liked.

However, one day, her peaceful routine was disrupted. Hearing her mother scream from the kitchen, she rushed in to find her mother on the ground, in pain. Her mother instructed her to take her to the hospital. With her mother's directions, she carried her to the car and drove her to the hospital. The hospital's antiseptic and sickly smells were overshadowed by her mother's condition. She quickly sought help from the doctors, who rushed to assist her mother, who had fallen from a stepladder while trying to reach a high cabinet.

This research aimed to demonstrate that sticking to a Mediterranean Diet (Med diet), indicated by a high "alternate Mediterranean" diet score, is linked to a lower risk of chronic heart disease (CHD) and stroke, as well as stroke-related deaths. The "alternate Mediterranean" diet is a modified Mediterranean diet, characterized by higher consumption of plant-based foods (excluding potatoes but including fruits, nuts, whole grains, and legumes), monounsaturated fats (instead of saturated fats), and fish, with lower intake of animal products and saturated fats. Moderate alcohol consumption is permitted.

Previous studies have shown that adherence to the Med diet is inversely associated with total and cardiovascular disease (CVD) mortality, and an intervention trial found the Med diet to be more effective than a low-fat diet in promoting weight loss and lowering the ratio of total to high-density lipoprotein cholesterol in overweight individuals. However, these prior studies did not concentrate on stroke or stroke mortality.

This study tracked 74,886 women aged 38 to 63, without a history of CVD or diabetes, who are part of the Nurses' Health Study, a cohort of 121,700 female nurses in 11 US states. Six times between 1984 and 2004, authors calculated an aMed diet score from self-reported "food frequency questionnaires" (FFQs) designed to estimate nutrient intake over the preceding year. Over 95% of participants maintained involvement throughout the 20-year period. FFQs underwent validation studies. Reports of CHD, fatal CHD, and stroke were verified by reviewing medical or hospital records, autopsy reports, or death certificates. When records were unavailable, cases were classified as "probable" and included, with about 17% of all strokes and 24% of nonfatal myocardial infarcts so classified. Body mass index, smoking status, aspirin use, multivitamin intake, menopausal status, and hormone use were calculated for each FFQ. Beginning in 1986, leisure-time physical activity was also assessed.

To minimize random variation for each individual and better represent long-term dietary intake, cumulative averages of the aMed score from the repeated FFQs were calculated (averaging scores from the previous two years). Adjustments were made for "confounders" (factors that might distort results) by accounting for age, smoking, BMI, menopausal status, hormone use, multivitamin intake, alcohol consumption, physical activity, and aspirin use.

Cox proportional-hazard modeling was used to examine the connection between the aMed score and risk of CHD and stroke, using separate models for fatal and nonfatal cases of CHD and stroke.

Greater adherence to the Mediterranean diet, as indicated by a higher aMed diet score, was associated with a lower risk of developing CHD and stroke in women. Over 20 years, 2391 new CHD cases, 1763 new stroke cases, and 1077 cardiovascular disease deaths (combined CHD and strokes) were identified. Women in the highest aMed quintile had a lower risk for both CHD and stroke compared to those in the lowest quintile (relative risk [RR], 0.71).

In 2007, the United States faced a severe financial crisis. Unemployment surged, the housing market collapsed, and many major American corporations were left in shambles. This recession continues today, prompting us to question: What caused this crisis, and how can we prevent it in the future? Essentially, the crisis stemmed from greedy and naive political decisions that pressured banks and firms to offer sub-prime loans despite the financial system's immaturity and inadequacy. Meanwhile, Fannie Mae (FNMA) and Freddie Mac (FHLMC) were urged to back and repack these mortgages into CDOs and CDSs. When borrowers defaulted, banks lacked adequate capital reserves, causing the chaos to spread to the repackaged mortgages they sold and, ultimately, to the broader economy.

The financial crisis can be traced back to 1999, during Bill Clinton's presidency, as he sought to secure a second term. To boost his popularity, the Clinton administration loosened lending restrictions, paving the way for the sub-prime crisis seven years later. Steven Holmes of the New York Times reported in 1999, "Fannie Mae, the nation's largest home mortgage underwriter, has faced increasing pressure from the Clinton Administration to expand mortgage loans to low and moderate-income individuals and from shareholders to maintain its remarkable profit growth." Holmes accurately predicted the consequences: "But the government-subsidized corporation may face trouble in an economic downturn, potentially requiring a government rescue similar to the one offered to the savings and loan industry in the 1980s." As mentioned earlier, and as Holmes foretold, imprudent lending would inevitably lead to an economic meltdown.

Several factors contributed to the economic downturn, including the complex mortgage structures used in the years leading up to the crisis. Adjustable-rate mortgages, mortgage-backed securities, and collateralized debt obligations (CDOs) were heavily used, further entangling various sectors of the economy with the housing market. This led to excessive leverage among U.S. households and financial markets, making them extremely sensitive to even minor price changes.

Indeed, the housing bubble burst, and financial institutions that had invested in mortgage-backed securities suffered significant losses. The top five U.S. investment banks collectively reported $4.1 trillion in mortgage debts in 2007, which accounted for about 30% of the USA's GDP. In the aftermath, Bear Stearns and Merrill Lynch were sold at bargain prices, Lehman Brothers was liquidated, and Goldman Sachs and Morgan Stanley were forced to become heavily regulated commercial banks. Fannie and Freddie, with $5 trillion in mortgage debt, were placed under government control in September 2008.

Exposition, that moment in your narrative where you take flight with your writing skills, captivating your audience with compelling prose, or that part where your readers lose focus and either nod off or hit the back button while grumbling about your writing. Dr. Merlin has been known to shout at her screen when she encounters excessive information, not even in an amusing way.

Exposition is not your friend.

My dear readers are probably already familiar with the writing advice, "Show, don't tell," but Dr. Merlin often falls into the trap of writing long passages where nothing significant happens, or even worse, too much. Exposition is that little voice in your head whispering to get the background out of the way to move on to the main events (not to be confused with the voice urging you to reveal every detail of your characters' histories).

Exposition involves conveying what happened to your audience, usually in straightforward language. In film, this occurs when one character provides a lengthy summary of information, like the monologue in "The Rime of the Ancient Mariner." In fiction, the author is the one doing the telling.

Let's take an example. While reading a story, you discover that the heroine met her love at a certain place and time, they wed in a grand manner, and her husband was slain in front of her. You wouldn't expect this entire sequence to take up two pages, during which they only have two lines of dialogue each. You would expect the author to delve into the husband's character, revealing his deep love for her through his words and actions, and show how his presence enriched her life. A proper introduction to his character would allow you to become emotionally invested in his fate and gain insight into the heroine's character: what she saw in him, their bond's depth, clues about her thoughts and beliefs as reflected through his eyes, and so on. You would mourn his death with her, growing more connected to the heroine herself.

In essence, you need to provide substance to the simple storyline: "They met, they married, he died."

As a writer, you have to offer that substance. (*looks at metaphor, sighs, presses on*) Sometimes it's tempting to rush past certain details. Perhaps you're introducing a new character and know he was once in the Air Force, now manages a night shift at a gas station, has been married twice, has no children, enjoys fishing on weekends, secretly dreams of owning the gas station someday, and had Eggs Benedict for breakfast.

I viewed two news broadcasts from Columbus, Ohio. The first, a live broadcast on NBC 4 this morning (August 13, 2011), covered a report about a man named Shad Hostettler in Ashley, Ohio, who had stabbed his wife. The name of the victim was not mentioned, but Hostettler's mugshot was shown, portraying him as "pure evil." The story was brief, lasting only two minutes, and provided limited details—he was arrested after stabbing her multiple times. I felt the time devoted to this story was sufficient. The second story concerned an early-morning shooting of Travis Buyers, an 18-year-old, in the Sharon Woods area. Buyers was critically injured, and no arrests were made. The SWAT team was investigating. This story seemed brief; I suspect this was due to the racial dynamics, as I've noticed that media coverage often differs when minorities are crime victims. The story about a Med-Flight helicopter with a .22 caliber rifle bullet hole was next, with Crime-Stoppers offering a $5,000 reward for the shooter's arrest. Another story addressed thunderstorms predicted for Saturday afternoon, with temperatures ranging from mid- to low-eighties, presented as a teaser to keep viewers interested. A robbery at a Clime Road UDF in Columbus was also covered, involving a dark-skinned black man in a hoodie. The man was described as six feet tall and 150 pounds, with more attention given to his race and skin color than usual. The final story was about Rene Rodriguez, a convicted drug kingpin sentenced to 300 months (or 25 years) for allegedly distributing large amounts of marijuana from Texas to Ohio. His Hispanic heritage was mentioned, but it wasn't clear why it was relevant to the story.

There exists a deep connection between brothers, an unshakable, immutable bond. Embedded within this bond are numerous emotions: affection, vanity, envy, and harshness, among others. Brothers comprehend one another, more so than any other bond, and can only see themselves mirrored in their brother's eyes. It is in times of greatest peril that the essence of this bond is revealed, whether for good or ill. When these emotions are laid bare, they exact a heavy toll. A part of grasping the feelings born of this fraternal tie involves coping with the repercussions they bring. When one can gaze into their brother's eyes and see their own reflection, they perceive themselves not as others see them, but as they truly are. Their actions and the consequences of those actions unveil their genuine character. In "The Scarlet Ibis," two brothers delve into this theme and the accompanying tumultuous emotions. Across a richly described landscape, these two boys embark on a doomed expedition. Bitter disappointment and intense pride collide in the climactic scene, and only one brother survives. The theme is conveyed through the direct portrayal of the protagonist, Doodle, and their interactions with each other, as well as through the narrator’s viewpoint, which communicates the protagonist's complex feelings and their perspective on the world, both of which greatly influence his actions.
	The protagonist's actions can be distilled into one dominant emotion: pride. From their first outing together to their final, fateful journey, the protagonist harbors resentment towards his younger brother, Doodle. He had wished for a brother to teach life skills like holding his breath, running, jumping, or climbing vines in Old Woman Swamp. He wanted a brother to compete with in races to Horsehead Landing and to perch with in the top fork of the great pine behind the barn. However, Doodle's severe heart condition made these dreams nearly impossible. The young protagonist, filled with wild fantasies, was crushed to realize these goals were unattainable. Even so, he harbored some anger towards the small child, recalling a moment when he considered suffocating him with a pillow. What kind of child could entertain such a thought? However, his heart softened when Doodle smiled at him. This simple act sparked hope within him, revealing that his conviction to harm was likely not strong. Deep down, he possessed an instinctive love for his brother.

The brain is a complex, inventive information-processing organ. As technology has evolved from rudimentary to advanced, so have the metaphors used to describe it. Initially, it was likened to a wax tablet, then to a sheet of parchment, then to a book, and most recently, to a computer. As you delve into brain studies, bear in mind that these metaphors are limited and can lead to faulty conclusions.
Information processing begins with input from your senses, which convert physical stimuli such as touch, heat, sound waves, or light particles into electrical signals. The sensory data is repeatedly processed by the brain through both hierarchical and feedback processes. For instance, when looking at a picture of a black box on a white background, hierarchical processing combines simple data like color, orientation, and object borders to identify it as a box. Feedback processing can then help you recognize it more quickly as a black box rather than a box-shaped hole in white.
Once information is processed, an attention mechanism decides its importance and which cognitive processes should access it. For example, while your brain scans every blade of grass when you look at your shoes, a healthy attention mechanism filters them out so you don't notice each one individually. However, you might pick out your name even in a noisy room. There are many stages of processing, and the results are repeatedly influenced by attention.
To process information, the brain must first store it. There are various types of memory, such as sensory, working, and long-term. Information is initially encoded based on the type of stimulus. For instance, verbal input can be encoded as visual, auditory, or semantic. Once stored, information must be kept, with working memory, which holds data for about 20 seconds, being maintained by a looping electrical signal through specific neurons. Long-term memory storage is hypothesized to involve certain proteins.
There are various theories on how knowledge is organized in the brain, drawing from different fields like psychology, computer science, and neurophysiology. The semantic network model posits that concepts are represented as nodes, with nodes linked based on their relatedness. For example, in a semantic network, "chair" might link to "table," which can link to "wooden," and so on.

Aldous Huxley critiques the impending danger of both technological advancements and the capitalist system that upholds them through the creation of a dystopian society in his novel Brave New World. The citizens of this society prioritize community over individuality and are conditioned from birth to seek immediate happiness above all else. People are revealed to be pawns in a larger game, confined to a singular ideology as dictated by the World Controller. Analyzing the work through a Marxist lens, one finds Huxley’s underlying concerns about the development of these systems. Terms like homogeneity and reification are frequently used to suggest that Huxley’s novel is a critique of the flaws in the emerging economy of his time.

Capitalism is satirized through the Marxist concept of false consciousness, which keeps the common people unaware of their true economic relations. Instead, they are focused on their own gain, a result of ideological control over the proletariat and common laborers, as seen in the conditioning of Brave New World’s citizens. The lower classes, such as Delta and Gamma, have no independent will; instead, hypnopædia encourages consumption and indulgence. The World Controller manipulates this, and the concept of hegemony, where one group dominates another, is evident. The lower classes are unaware of this manipulation, “buying into” the ideology that supports capitalism and consumerism. The upper classes, such as Alphas and Betas, also accept their place, with few exceptions like Bernard. The interactions between social classes indicate the perceived oppression of capitalism. Relationships between individuals are superficial, as seen in characters’ comments focusing on physical appearance and encounters. The citizens’ complacency with their social status suggests the socioeconomic effects of capitalism, with Marxist thought on the proletariat being reinforced, as they are made to believe in their superiority through continued consumption and obedience.

I've been a University Park student for approximately two and a half years, or four and a half semesters. Navigating around campus can be challenging for many students, including myself. My first year, I stayed in an East Halls dorm, the easternmost residential area on campus, excluding the stadium and Bryce Jordan Center. It could take up to 25 minutes to walk from my dorm to classes in distant locations like the Willard Building, especially when it's bad weather, which is common in State College. An older alumni told me that in the past, East Halls was separated from the main campus by vast, underutilized lands. Now, those spaces have been developed into sports fields, new structures like the Creamery and health services building, and apartments, as the campus continues to grow. This expansion has made movement around campus increasingly difficult.

The solution to this mobility issue lies in cycling, but it's not effective unless students use bicycles and the campus is designed to accommodate them. My friend, who recently restarted cycling after years of hiatus, agreed that bikes are the best way to get around campus. Apart from being good for health, cycling is also the most efficient mode of transport. A bowl of oatmeal and a bit of exercise can take you 30 miles or more. I currently live off-campus, equidistant from the center as some dorms. The best decision I've made this year was to buy a bike. Usually, it takes me 25 minutes to walk to my classes in Thomas building. Biking can reduce this time to 5 minutes if I pedal quickly. However, Pollock Road, the most direct route to Thomas, isn't always easy to bike on. While walking also has its advantages, I lack the time due to my busy schedule. If I didn't have my bike, walking would be my only option, adding an extra 30-40 minutes to my daily routine, which amounts to over two and a half hours each week, not to mention the time spent walking to other classes, appointments, and more.
